05263nam a22006255i 9780822374015DE-B159720200928045905.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200928t20172017ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016045052  a97808223740157 a10.1515/97808223740152doi  a(DE-B1597)554637  a(OCoLC)1198930848  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aML3916b.I47 2017 4aML3916b.I47 2017 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a781.3/622300aImprovisation and Social Aesthetics /cGeorgina Born, Will Straw, Eric Lewis. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b12 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aImprovisation, community, and social practice00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION What Is Social Aesthetics? -- tCHAPTER 1 After Relational Aesthetics: Improvised Music, the Social, and (Re)Theorizing the Aesthetic -- tCHAPTER 2 Scripting Social Interaction: Improvisation, Performance, and Western "Art" Music -- tCHAPTER 3 From the American Civil Rights Movement to Mali: Reflections on Social Aesthetics and Improvisation -- tCHAPTER 4 From Network Bands to Ubiquitous Computing: Rich Gold and the Social Aesthetics of Interactivity -- tCHAPTER 5 The Social Aesthetics of Swing in the 1940s: Or the Distribution of the Non-Sensible -- tCHAPTER 6 What Is "Great Black Music"? The Social Aesthetics of the AACM in Paris -- tCHAPTER 7 Kenneth Goldsmith and Uncreative Improvisation -- tCHAPTER 8 Strayhorn's Queer Arrangements -- tCHAPTER 9 What's Love Got to Do with It? Creating Art, Creating Community, Creating a Better World -- tCHAPTER 10 Improvisation in New Wave Cinema: Beneath the Myth, the Social -- tCHAPTER 11 Social Aesthetics and Transcultural Improvisation: Wayde Compton and the Performance of Black Time -- tCHAPTER 12 Devices of Existence: Contact Improvisation, Mobile Performances, and Dancing through Twitter -- tCHAPTER 13 The Dramaturgy of Spontaneity: Improvising the Social in Theater -- tReferences -- tContributors' Biographies -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAddressing a wide range of improvised art and music forms-from jazz and cinema to dance and literature-this volume's contributors locate improvisation as a key site of mediation between the social and the aesthetic. As a catalyst for social experiment and political practice, improvisation aids in the creation, contestation, and codification of social realities and identities. Among other topics, the contributors discuss the social aesthetics of the Association for the Advancement of Creative Musicians, the Feminist Improvising Group, and contemporary Malian music, as well as the virtual sociality of interactive computer music, the significance of "uncreative" improvisation, responses to French New Wave cinema, and the work of figures ranging from bell hooks and Billy Strayhorn to Kenneth Goldsmith. Across its diverse chapters, Improvisation and Social Aesthetics argues that ensemble improvisation is not inherently egalitarian or emancipatory, but offers a potential site for the cultivation of new forms of social relations. It sets out a new conceptualization of the aesthetic as immanently social and political, proposing a new paradigm of improvisation studies that will have reverberations throughout the humanities.Contributors. Lisa Barg, Georgina Born, David Brackett, Nicholas Cook, Marion Froger, Susan Kozel, Eric Lewis, George E. Lewis, Ingrid Monson, Tracey Nicholls, Winfried Siemerling, Will Straw, Zoë Svendsen, Darren Wershler  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAestheticsxSocial aspects. 0aArts and society. 0aImprovisation (Music)xSocial aspects. 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticis